\par }{\ul Smoke in the Granary}{
\par 
\par Grandpa: We got down in that old broken tin granary and built a fire.
\par 
\par Linda: In the granary?
\par 
\par Grandpa: Yeah, yeah, yes sir. Then, we smoked all those dukes on some sacks . . . tried to put the fire out. There was lots of smoke. By then, I couldn\rquote t see. By
 then, we got great big green flames under that granary. The wind took it. . . . the fire . . . The smoke was so bad; . . . By then I was so sick I didn\rquote t care. And that guy, he wasn\rquote t very religious, anyway. He said, \'93can you pray.\'94
 I said, \'93I don\rquote t know if I can or not,\'94 He said, \'93Be quiet, I will.\'94 \'93We better start praying,\'94 he says. \'93We gotta put that fire out or I\rquote ll get a whippen.\'94 So I said, \'93How are we going to do it?\'94 \'93
Throw dirt on it,\'94 he said. Well, we had it right in the middle of a rock pile. So we threw the rocks on it. And it didn\rquote t put the fire out. So he said, \'93We\rquote ll run down the hill (to get some dirt).\'94
 Oh, which pretty near the length of this building (the Elks Hospital). We had to run fast to get it out. . . . It burnt faster. Oh boy!
\par 
\par Linda: Did you get the fire out?
\par 
\par Grandpa: No, we didn\rquote t. Harvey Simons was over there working his grass line and he looked up and he said, \'93Hey you guys\endash put that fire out.\'94 . . . And there we sat. \'93Well, we gotta get this fire out, . . . bags of . . . and
 here comes Harvey Simons.\'94 And I shout, \'93If Dad\rquote s doesn\rquote t whip me this time for this misdemeanor I\rquote d never smoke it again,\'94 and I didn\rquote t. He didn\rquote t whip me and I didn\rquote t smoke no more of this foolishness.

\par 
\par 
\par }{\ul Moonshine}{
\par 
\par I went with those boys downtown one night. And they had this moonshine. They got a couple of bottle of it. They wanted me to drink with them. I told them I don\rquote 
t want to drink that garbage. You go ahead and drink it and they did and they got drunk. They were drunk. . . . hung around there they were lazy. There you know\endash 
they were truing to sober up so they dared to go home. I finally I took off and went home. And left them.
\par 
\par Mom said, \'93Where have you been?\'94 when I came in. I said I went with the boys downtown \endash  mom said what did you do? Well, I knew right then I\rquote d have to tell her. I said, well they had some moonshine . . . I says well, I didn\rquote 
t drink any but the rest of them did and they are pretty souped up. I said, I didn\rquote t want to stay around there while they sobered up so I came home. Mom to
ld Carlyn and Berdise and they went down and told all the mothers of those kids that their kids had been on a bender. And the they were going to beat me up for telling on them. 
\par 
\par Bryce: If you didn\rquote t get it one way you got it another.
\par 
\par Grandpa: I told them right out, I says, you guy know you are doing wrong so what do you want to beat me up for. You knew better. They kind of cooled down and didn\rquote t beat me up. I didn\rquote 
t go fool with them anymore. Because they wanted to drink and go crazy like that they could do it all by themselves. So I got very unpopular. 
\par 
\par I didn\rquote t like what they were doing to all the girls in the ward anyway. There wasn\rquote t a one of them down there they didn\rquote t play with or whatever you call it.
\par 
\par And I said well, I don\rquote t want any of them anyway \endash  they are second handed. So I wouldn\rquote t go with them and they kept messing with them and finally they went off to Wellsville and found them a wife and left the home kids high and dry 
\endash  and I didn\rquote t think that was good either. I finally moved away and ended up in Riverside and that\rquote s where Mom was, so I married her.
\par 
\par }{\ul 1}{\ul\super st}{\ul  Job
\par }{
\par First job pitching tater bags. Handle very good. 68 cents an hour. And I thought I was doing good. 
\par 
\par Linda: It was in those days.
\par 
\par Grandpa: Boy, I well we could pay our bills and that\rquote s about all. With what we got paid.
\par 
\par How soon was it after you got married that you we to Arco and broke that land out of Sagebrush.
\par 
\par Grandpa: Well, we went up there the first year we were married and that was 1941. Spring of 1941 
we went up there and worked with Wilkee Noble that summer and well between Wilkee and me we got grandpa Moses 80 acres planted and for the next year we moved back to Riverside for the winter. Next year we moved up there in that old ram shock of a house. J
e
sse T came up there with Bings, storming around with little faith that we would get it fixed. So we got one room fixed and moved in. And that was the end of Jesse T. He took off and left me to fix the rest of it. So we plastered and patched the holes in t
he the bedroom, then we had two rooms done and we fixed up another room and we had three rooms. And that was as far as I got. We bought the 40 then so we decided we\rquote 
d ren grandpa Moses place one more year and live there and live there and farm the 40 and I\rquote ll be damed if grandpa didn\rquote 
t sell it out from under us. And left us hight and driy. No house to live in and no nothing. The 40 acres we bought had a one-room.
\par 
\par We were all in that one room and I told Leone, I said, \'93we can\rquote t go on much longer. We can\rquote t li
ve here like this all summer and that was in the spring. I went over to Wilkee and he had a bunch of old beat up cinder blocks. I told him if he would let me use them I would build my house and then in the fall I would replace them when it. .. In the fall
 
when we got that trade done and went down to Boise Payette lumber, only it was in Arco. I knew that guy pretty well and he loaned me about $1,500 worth of credit on lumber and stuff and we built that house on the highway. So between that we had about $5,0
00 in that shock when we got it done. But it was so warm. Wind and snow blowing in the wintertime inside there you couldn\rquote 
t tell if it was whistling or what. We had that warm mouning stove and we could fill that thing full at night and it would burn all night and half the next day and we never got cold in that building. I had it insulated on top 6 inches.
\par 
\par 
\par THIS IS A PAGE OUT OF ORDER:
\par 
\par I bought a real killer diller from that sucker old \'93run away at the drop of a hat.\'94 I hooked him up one day and Brownie together and that was a mistake.
\par 
\par NEW PAGE:
\par 
\par Its about supposed to be 6 inches of insulation in these . . . about that many . . . we put over them we went up there and put some more on top. We put white pine on the ceiling and we didn\rquote t like that so we plaste
red over the top of it. It was really a pretty warm houme with cinder blocks all the way around. It didn\rquote t take much to heat that thing. It the best \endash  the really the best home we\rquote ve ever had except for we built it for a garage.
\par 
\par I ... one two three four ro
oms and a bathroom and the kitchen was last the living south bathroom outside door was right there. You walked in that doorway and was in the living or the Kitchen. The kitchen was here and the livingroom and you could go either way. Most the time we head
ed for the kitchen cause thats where the food was.
\par 
